definition.value: A 4-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is shikimic acid in which the allylic hydroxy group has been oxidised to the corresponding keto group.

A benzylisoquinoline alkaloid that is 6-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydro[1,3]dioxolo[4,5-g]isoquinoline which is substituted at the 5-pro-S position by a (6R)-8-oxo-6,8-dihydrofuro[3,4-e][1,3]benzodioxol-6-yl group. A light-sensitive competitive antagonist of GABAA receptors. It was originally identified in 1932 in plant alkaloid extracts and has been isolated from Dicentra cucullaria, Adlumia fungosa, Fumariaceae, and several Corydalis species.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from one of the carboxylic acid groups of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric acid.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of glutaric acid.
An oxo dicarboxylic acid comprising glutaric acid having oxo- and hydroxy substituents at the 2- and 4-positions respectively.
A tartaric acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-carboxy-2,3-dihydroxypropanoate.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of cis-3-(2-chloro-3,3,3-trifluoroprop-1-enyl)-2,2-dimethylcyclopropanecarboxylic acid and [(2-methyl-1,1'-biphenyl)-3-yl]methanol.
A carboxyalkyl phosphate that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a 3-phosphonooxy group.
A citramalate(2-) that is the conjugate base of D-citramalic acid.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is pyruvic acid substituted at position 3 by a phospho group.
A citramalate(2-) that is the conjugate acid of L-citramalic acid.
The 5alpha,9alpha,10beta-diastereomer of copalyl diphosphate.
A dTDP-sugar having 4-dehydro-2,6-dideoxy-D-glucose as the sugar component.
A dideoxyhexose that is L-arabinohexose in which the hydroxy groups at positions 3 and 6 are replaced by hydrogen.
A potassium salt which is the monopotassium salt of thiocyanic acid.
An organic sodium salt which is the monosodium salt of thiocyanic acid.
A diazine that is benzene in which the carbon atoms at positions 1 and 4 have been replaced by nitrogen atoms.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which all three methyl hydrogens are substituted by chlorine.
A pyridoxate that is the conjugate base of 4-pyridoxic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A benzoate ester in which 4-amino-3-butoxybenzoic acid and 2-(diethylamino)ethanol have combined to form the ester bond; an ester-based local anaesthetic (ester "caine") used especially in ophthalmology and otolaryngology.

A organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 10H-benzo[b]xanthene-7,10,12-trione substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 6 and 11, methoxy groups at positions 3 and 8 and a methyl group at position 1.
A pyridoxate that is the conjugate base of 5-pyridoxic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The hydrochloride salt of pyridoxine.
A saturated organic heteromonocyclic parent that is a four-membered ring comprising of three carbon atoms and an oxygen atom.
